title: For Sale:  K98k Mauser, 1943 Gustloff bcd43, RC
postcontent:
A very nice Russian Capture K98k.  Gustloff Werke "bcd."  It has very clean WaA and subcontractor markings on all metal parts.  The stock has been scrubbed of WaA unfortunately.   Gustloff used all subcontractors and this one has many of the correct subcontracted parts.  It also has the correct style of major part for a 1943 Gustloff (speed milled upper band, cupped buttplate on laminated stock, milled trigger housing, etc) The "X" indicating Russian capture is a well struck Serif "X." 

It is import marked at the barrel.  Does not have sight hood, cleaning rod or capture screws (as is typical of RC rifles). A VERY nice example, especially compared to the very beat up and peened examples coming in these days.  Even those will be drying up shortly I fear.

If you want an economical, historic entry into collecting K98s this is a very nice one to start with.

$440 FTF.  Will meet a reasonable distance.

title: For Sale:  Ed Brown Special Forces 1911 with rail - rare
postcontent:
A used, and carried, but well-maintained pistol from a top-tier manufacturer of 1911's.  Ed Brown no longer makes this particular model, and they are difficult to find.  Ed Brown claims 1-1/2" accuracy at 50 yards, and although I am not that caliber of shooter I believe it.  The big thing with Ed Brown, is it is not super-tight, just tight where it matters, so they run!  There was no break-in period, I've had Kimbers and the like that are accurate, but if you don't run them really wet you will experience malfunctions, especially for the first 500-1,000 rounds.  I've run this pistol wet, but also after it's been in the holster for weeks and seems dry, and I've yet to have this pistol malfunction.  I think with regular drops of oil in the right places, and quality magazines/ammo, this firearm will run flawlessly for thousands of rounds, until the recoil spring or magazine spring is ready for replacement.  This would likely be a great pistol for IDPA or USPSA, as well as carry.  The trigger on this is really sweet, again Ed Brown says they ship at 3.5 pounds, and it is very crisp and clean.

Comes with tritium Night sites, Gen3 coating (over stainless, so you don't have to worry as much about sweat, etc when carrying), light/laser rail, cocobolo grips, Ed Brown exclusive chain link on front and rear strap, factory 7 round magazine, and carrying case with all paperwork and the oil, etc that came with the pistol.

As I carried this, there are some wear marks from the holster, but nothing too ugly in my opinion, I've made sure they all show in the pictures, however some artifacts in the pictures that look like flaws are lighting or oil (typical for my photography skills).

title: For Sale:  Weatherby PA-459 TR with Holographic Sight, 630 Lumen Torch & Laser
location: NE Fort Wayne, Fort Wayne, Indiana
postcontent: The Title really says it all, but if you're not familiar with shotguns, Weatherby is considered the Cadillac of Shotguns as far as quality goes, and this is one of their first Tactical Lines of Shotguns offered strictly for Tactical Use (home or personal defense, military or LE, Etc). It comes stock with a Ghost Ring Rear sight (fully adjustable for windage & elevation along with a Truglo Fiber Optic Green Front Sight on a Post similar to an AR-15 "A" Post. It's also got a tactical choke tube that acts as a flash suppressor, but also has teeth for "biting" into doorknobs & locks you may need to shoot out. I've fired all types of rounds from this gun from Slugs to OOO Buck & found it to be exceedingly accurate, easy to shoot, and most importantly it has a good solid recoil reducing rubber backed stock that won't leave a welt on your shoulder. I prefer pump action to any other type of shotgun for reliablity & while this gun advertises that its setup for 2 3/4" & 3" Magnum Rounds, I've actually loaded 3 1/2" Magnum rounds in it singly by hand & it worked beautifully with no problems at all, you just need to feed the round right into the chamber to do it safely & effectively.  Personally though I don't see the need to ever really use a 3 1/2" Magnum round when you can get a good 12-Pellet 2 3/4" round that fires 12 .357 caliber rounds that spread out the farther you are from your target & with this gun you get a nice even circular spread, each travelling around 1,200fps, so even if only one of these rounds hits your intended target you're probably going to drop him on the spot, and that's a poor shot. Imagine what an aimed, decent shot with this same ammo can do.  Goto a 3" round & you can get a 15 pellet OO Buck Shot that increases your chances of a hit & highly increases the chances of a deadly stop in your target's tracks too.  You can liken it to dumping a full 15rd clip from a Glock 31 .357SIG, except all at the same time with all the bullets spreading out the further they travel in a circular pattern until they strike the target. You need not be a good shot with a shotgun to hit your target, but that being said this shotgun with it's ghost ring & Truglo Front Sight make it really easy to be deadly accurate with each & every shot. I just took it one step further by adding some extras, such as the Holographic sight (the shotgun comes with picatinny rail installed on top in front of the sight so you can opt to use any type of RDS or HWS you like instead of the stock sights.  Add the blinding 630 Lumen Torch & a Red Laser that you can switch to run independently or together & you've got the ultimate tactical shotgun. I'm even throwing in a pressure switch you can mount on the guns pump forearm or wherever you feel most comfortable mounting it so you don't need to fumble around to switch on the torch or laser.  Goodluck & feel free to contact me with any questions. I am open to trades for other weapons, particularly I'd like to get a good .357 or .44 magnum, or even a Ruger Mini-14 GB, but am open to any other ideas, and I also take all major credit cards.  Shipment anywhere in the lower 48 for $39.99.

title: For Sale:  Individual sale of handguns do require a permit to purchase or a NC CCH.
postcontent:
There is a guy posting on here that you only need a bill of sale for a handgun purchase and that is WRONG!!  In NC for individual to individual sales of handguns the buyer must present the seller with a valid Permit To Purchase or the buyer must show the seller a valid NC Concealed Handgun Permit. The concealed permit has to be a NC license and not another state. Also Federal Law only allows sales of handguns to residents of your own state. 

Read Section B starting on page 4 of this NCGS:

http://www.ncdoj.gov/getdoc/32344299-a2a7-4ae5-99fd-9018262f64ac/NC-Firearms-gun-Laws.aspx

I'm just trying to help everyone out and keep websites like this up and running so the gun grabbers don't start trying to say these websites are used for illegal gun sales when we just want a place we can buy, sell, and trade items in the sport that we all love.
